A logical upper limit helps put a constraint on what can feasibly be manufactured. When you make a product, different inputs help manufacture it (labor hours, materials, etc.) and each of the inputs has a limit on how much is availible over a certain period of time. So asking one worker in one business day to manufacture 10,000 bicycles all by himself is unrealistic because it is beyond his means of workable hours in that day. He may still be able to manufacture that many bicycles, but it may take him several weeks instead.
The logical upper limit comes in handy when you are considering a product mix model. Many of the different product your business makes may utilize the same materials, so deciding which product are the most profitable and how much you have in the way of inputs is vital to making the decision of what to make, and how much of it to produce. Having the logical upper limit helps put the constraint in of the maximum of each product that can be possibly made given the inputs availible.
